  <title>Graphig Logarithmic Functions</title>
    <subsection>
      <title>Defining the Logarithm Function</title>
      <p>Since we can find the base <m>10</m> logarithm of any positive real number, we can use logarithms to define a function.  We define a logarithmic function as follows:
      <md>
        <mrow>f(x) = \log(x)</mrow>
      </md>
      this function pairs every positive <m>x</m>-value with the base <m>10</m> logarithm of that <m>x</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>Table of values and graph of <m>f(x) = \log(x)</m></caption>

        <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" margins="auto" valign="top">
          <tabular top="major" halign="center">
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell halign="left"><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(x)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>0.001</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(0.001)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>0.01</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(0.01)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>0.1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(0.1)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(1)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>10</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(10)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell halign="left"><m>100</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(100)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row bottom="major">
              <cell halign="left"><m>1000</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\log(1000)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <image>
            <latex-image-code>
              <![CDATA[
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                  xlabel = x,
                  ylabel = f(x),
                  ylabel near ticks,
                  xlabel near ticks,
                  xmin = 0,
                  ]

                  \addplot [thick, blue, <->, mark=none, domain=0.1:15,samples=100] {log10(x)};

                  \addplot[only marks, color=magenta] coordinates {
                  (0.001,  -3)
                  (0.01,  -2)
                  (0.1,  -1)
                  (1,  0)
                  (10,  1)
                  };

                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image-code>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </figure>

    <p>The ordered pairs highlighted on the graph are all of the form <m>\left( a, \log(a) \right)</m>. Consider the pairs with the input and output interchanged: <m>(-3,0.001), (-2,0.01), (-1,0.1), (0,1), (1,10), (2,100), (3,1000)</m>. These new pairs are associated with the base <m>10</m> exponential function <m>g(x) = 10^x</m>.
    </p>

